<Class name="CM_FixupHandlerAgent" id="7d9b51bd-8bf6-4d0b-9b9f-a4b62e0b8352">
    <superclass name="CM_Agent"/>
    <transient/>
    <persistentAllowed/>
    <sharedTransientAllowed/>
    <subclassPersistentAllowed/>
    <subclassSharedTransientAllowed/>
    <subclassTransientAllowed/>
    <transientAllowed/>
    <text>
	Used by "CMUI_FixupHandlerForm".
	
	Add a method to do the work (see doRepairShipReceivalTrans as an example).
	
	Add a reference to your method and a nice name (that the users will see on the form) to the method 'zGetNiceName'.
	
	Any methods you don't want the users to see should be made protected. (i.e. any methods on this class called
	by your main repair method should be protected. )  Protected methods will not show in the special methods combo on the form.
	
	Methods starting with 'z' are for use by the form and will not show in the special methods combo on the form.
	
	Make sure that the default action of your method when run with no parameters entered
	is to show instructions only.
	
	In the instructions refer back to the related par, so that the user can read more if they wish to.
	
	If the task is going to update data, make sure that you provide a list type function and recommend
	to the user that they run this first so that the user can determine what will happen and effectively
	accept responsibility for the update.</text>
    <DbClassMap file="fixup"/>
    <Constant name="DeleteOperation" id="674b9d84-e871-4821-946a-bd79f5005900">
        <source>"DELETE"</source>
        <type name="String"/>
    </Constant>
    <Constant name="FindOperation" id="b3850991-f547-476f-a1f0-5fd5e30aeae7">
        <source>"FIND"</source>
